Rating: 3
This is very good, but I have a few technique issues with the recipe. First of all I never sweat eggplant. There is just no need. Nicholas Clee, the British author of "Don't Sweat the Aubergine" (Short Books, 2005), argues that salting probably is unnecessary given the relatively mild bitterness of most of the eggplants available today. Also, salt extracts only as much bitterness as it does moisture: that is, not much. It also leaves the eggplant too salty. Also, I cut the slices much thicker. You want to taste the eggplant, don't you?

